Date: 16 Mar 2005
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: The Washington Times [edited]
<http://washingtontimes.com/upi-breaking/20050316-084441-9433r.htm>

Anthrax worries not over in Virginia
------------------------------------
"We're talking 2 different incidences," said Merni Fitzgerald,
spokeswoman for the National Capitol Region Joint Information Center.
"There are 2 different things: the Pentagon and Skyline." Anthrax
tests at U.S. Defense Department office buildings in Fairfax,
Virginia are not complete, and the buildings will remain closed, a
spokeswoman said today [16 Mar 2005].
Some 70 tests done since Monday [14 Mar 2005] have cleared anthrax
worries at the Pentagon, located in Arlington, Virginia, but results
were not in from tests at the separate Department of Defense-leased
Skyline office buildings to the west in Fairfax County.
"We're talking 2 different incidences," said Merni Fitzgerald,
spokeswoman for the National Capitol Region Joint Information Center.
"There are 2 different things: the Pentagon and Skyline," Fitzgerald
told United Press International. "The protocols are on a different
time line because the Pentagon incident was earlier. At the Pentagon,
the testing is completed and results were negative. The Skyline
protocol is continuing, and there are still tests pending at Skyline."
Fitzgerald said the Skyline buildings would remain closed until
testing and protocols are completed. "At that point, the Fairfax
County health director will make a decision about the status of the
buildings," she said. "Of course, that will be based on the results
of the testing and the protocols. I cannot really predict when the
tests will come back."
--
