[Now the finger-pointing starts, and folk grab facts that support
their assumptions and presumptions. From these reports, I note the
following: "...10:30 a.m. Monday [14 Mar 2005], when a defense
contractor responsible for daily biohazard monitoring at the Pentagon
mail room reported a positive alert for anthrax from a sensor filter
sampled Thursday [10 Mar 2005]; and "...but analysis of more than 70
samples subsequently taken from [Pentagon facility] filters, surfaces
and machines at both mail rooms showed no trace of anthrax bacteria,
living or dead." At some point, a _B. anthracis_ product apparently
entered the testing system. "The test that produced the confirmed
positive finding of anthrax was performed by the U.S. Army Medical
Research Institute of Infectious Diseases at Fort Detrick and
completed at about 4 a.m. yesterday [15 Mar 2005], a top military
official said. The polymerase chain reaction test is accurate to
"very, very close" to 100 percent in confirming the presence of the
molecular signature of anthrax bacteria, he said. But all subsequent
lab culture tests, used to determine whether there were any live or
viable bacteria, were negative." Note, this does not state that they
did not find dead _B. anthracis_. On the other hand, if this had been
a repeat of the 2001 incidents, there would have been no lack of
positive samples, alive or dead. At this time, there is no public
information on the nature of the various tests run.
And let us take comfort from the fact that liaison screw-ups
apparently continued, which means that no one will be sitting back
complacent that "the system" works. But, in the end, it is the
responsibility of those on the sand in the arena who have to make the
decisions. The rest of us must watch and learn from the event. And, in your
prayers, remember my friend John Ezell and his staff at USAMRIID, who will
be the subject of intense scrutiny. There, but for the grace of God, go many
of us. - Mod.MHJ]
[There must be something wrong with the reported test time line: "...10:30
a.m. Monday [14 Mar 2005], when a defense contractor responsible for daily
biohazard monitoring at the Pentagon mail room reported a positive alert for
anthrax from a sensor filter sampled Thursday [10 Mar 2005]." Is it a fact
that the mail room is not used on Friday through Sunday, and employees do
not report to work until after 10:30 a.m. Monday, so such test results will
give timely warning? - Mod.JW]
